Boil your #kettle{}. Pick the @tarragon{1/4}(leaves picked and finely chopped) and finely chop (discard the stalks). Remove the root and dark green tops from the @leek{2}(root and dark green tops removed), halve lengthways, then slice into thin half moons. Season the @British pork loin steaks{2} on both sides with a large pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @ground black pepper{pinch}. Dissolve the @chicken stock powder{1/2} in a #measuring jug{} with the @water{100}(boiling).

Put a large #saucepan{} of water with a @salt{pinch} on to boil. Cut the @salad potatoes{350} in half, or quarters if there are any big ones (no need to peel!) and pop them in your pan of boiling water. Cook for ~{15-20%minutes}. TIP: The potato is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through. Drain the potatoes in a #colander{} and set aside.

Heat a splash of @oil{2%splash} in a #frying pan{} on high heat. Add the leek with a @salt{pinch} and stir-fry until soft, ~{4-5%minutes}. Remove the leek from the pan once nice and soft, cover with some #foil{} to keep warm.

Add another splash of @oil{2%splash} to your now empty pan and return it to high heat. Once hot, add the pork and fry for ~{2%minutes} on each side. Next, pour in the stock and add the tarragon. Stir well to get any meaty bits from the base of the pan. Simmer until the liquid has reduced by a third, ~{6-8%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The pork is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle. Be careful not to over reduce the liquid!

Turn the heat to low, add the @soured cream{75} and stir. TIP: Make sure the sauce does not boil as this could curdle the cream. Allow everything to warm through. Test for seasoning and add more @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} if needed.

Serve the new potatoes on a #plate{} with the leek scattered over them. Place a pork medallion on top and pour over the tarragon sauce. Et voilà!

> Simple is best in this dish. Creamy and comforting, this delicious recipe from our Head Chef Andre is the perfect thing for chilly evenings at home. Tarragon, stock, and sour cream are gently combined to create a velvety sauce that works brilliantly with golden pan-fried pork steaks, buttery leeks and new potatoes.